   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6">Stack/Queue Conversion</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_2" text:outline-level="2">Learning Report</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6">The first thing I had to learn was that an expression tree, although a binary tree, is not a binary search tree. I spent so much time working and figuring to make the underlying tree structure a BST-type structure only to realize that I had wasted my time. Note tht the delete node method still remain even they aren&apos;t really needed; it used to de-allocate memory for the destructor.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6">I also learned that stacks/queues are fundamental to these structures. <text:span text:style-name="T4">I could be wrong, but parsing expressions seem to demand them (or some cruder mechanism that implement the same functionality. Much time was dedicated to this task as well.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7">In general, I learned that I don&apos;t really understand trees <text:s/>that well and that I will need to dedicate a lot of real estate on my exam notes to the topic.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"/>
  </office:text>
 </office:body>
</office:document>